{{Infobox language | name = Sakizaya | nativename = | states = [[Taiwan]] | region = | ethnicity = [[Sakizaya people|Sakizaya]] | speakers = 913 | date = 2017 | familycolor = Austronesian | fam2 = [[East Formosan languages|East Formosan]] | fam3 = Ami | script = | iso3 = —<ref group=note>[[ISO 639-3]] code ''ais'' is assigned to "Nataoran Amis" by SIL/Ethnologue. However, the government of the Republic of China uses this code for the Sakizayan language.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}</ref> | iso3comment = | map = Formosan languages 2008.png | mapcaption = (purple) Greater Ami. Nataoran and Sakizaya are in the north. | notice = | glotto = saki1247 | glottorefname = Sakizaya }}
'''Sakizaya''' is a [[Formosan languages|Formosan language]] closely related to [[Amis language|Amis]].
== History == After the [[:zh:加禮宛事件|Takobowan Incident]] of 1876, the [[Sakizaya people]] hid among the Nataoran Amis, and the Sakizaya language was thus categorized as a dialect of Amis.
In 2002, the Center of Aboriginal Studies of [[National Chengchi University]] in Taiwan corrected this error when they edited the indigenous languages textbooks. Therefore, that year Sakizaya language was designated both as a Chilai and Amis sublanguage.<ref>[http://alilin.apc.gov.tw/tw/ebooks?view=adm_ebook&id=324 Textbooks] by the Council of Indigenous Peoples in Taiwan</ref> On 17 January 2007, the Taiwan government recognised the Sakizaya community as the thirteenth distinct indigenous ethnic group.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6271819.stm Taiwan recognises 'lost' people.] BBC News. Retrieved on January 19, 2007</ref>
940 people are registered as Sakizaya.<ref>[https://www.apc.gov.tw/portal/docDetail.html?CID=940F9579765AC6A0&DID=2D9680BFECBE80B6B1BE41CEAE99B007 中華民國原住民族委員會], 2018年6月23日查閱</ref> They live in the Takubuwan, Sakur, Maifor and Kaluluwan communities. Thousands of others are still registered as Amis. Around half of Amis politicians in Hualian, the biggest Amis city, are actually Sakizaya.
==Controversies== Sakizaya language is officially classified as a dialect of [[Nataoran language|Nataoran Amis]] by the international standard-keeper of [[SIL International|SIL]]/[[Ethnologue]],<ref>[https://www.ethnologue.com/language/ais Nataoran at Ethnologue]</ref> but in the statement from the Taiwan government,<ref>[http://apc.sce.ntnu.edu.tw/abst/files/1504579855_piQrv.pdf General regulations for Test of Taiwan Indigenous Languages], 2017, Council of Indigenous Peoples in Taiwan</ref> the language is separate from Amis and no other dialect descends from Sakizaya.
