{{Infobox patriarch | name=Theodosius Romanus | image= | patriarch_of=[[Syriac Orthodox Church of Antioch|Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch and All the East]] | church=[[Syriac Orthodox Church]] | see=[[Antioch]] | enthroned =887 | ended=896 | predecessor =[[Ignatius II]] | successor=[[Dionysius II of Antioch|Dionysius II]] | birth_name=Romanus | birth_date = | birth_place =[[Tikrit|Tagrit]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]] | death_date=1 June 896 | death_place= | residence = | alma_mater = | other = | footnotes = }} '''Theodosius Romanus''' (died 1 June 896) was the [[Patriarch of Antioch]], and head of the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] from 887 until his death in 896.
==Biography== Romanus was born in the 9th century in the city of Tagrit and later went on to become a monk at the [[Mor Gabriel Monastery|Monastery of Qartmin]] where he also studied and mastered medicine to the point that he became known as a skilled physician.
The synod of the Syriac Orthodox Church met in the city of [[Diyarbakır|Amid]] and elected and consecrated Romanus as patriarch on 5 February 887, upon which he adopted the name Theodosius. During his tenure as patriarch, Theodosius Romanus ordained 32 [[metropolitan bishops]], and served as patriarch until his death on 1 June 896.
==Works== Theodosius' work includes a lengthy commentary on Pseudo-Hierotheus, the first two treatises of which he wrote whilst staying at [[Amid]] before finishing the third treatise at [[Samosata]]. He also wrote a treatise explaining the maxims of various philosophers, including a collection 112 Pythagorean maxims, most of which he had translated from [[Greek language|Greek]] into [[Syriac language|Syriac]].
As well as this, Theodosius is known to have written a medical syntagma, a synodical epistle and a Lenten homily in [[Arabic language|Arabic]].
